{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/adapters/fs.rs:2103-2111` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:2254-2264` create `milestones/<id>/` just to take the per-milestone lock, before any existence check runs. Any typoed `update_status`/`persist_plan`/`record_bead_start`/`update_task_run` call will therefore leave behind an empty milestone directory plus `mutation.lock`; after that, `FsMilestoneStore::milestone_exists` (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2131-2142`) treats the ID as corrupt, so `create_milestone` can no longer create that milestone without manual cleanup.","rationale":"This is a real correctness bug: failed mutations against a missing milestone poison the workspace and block later creation of the same milestone id."},{"body":"`read_task_runs_from_path` never verifies that each deserialized `TaskRunEntry.milestone_id` matches the milestone file being read (`src/adapters/fs.rs:2478-2500`). Downstream code then trusts those rows for both snapshot reconciliation (`src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:163-223`) and the new bead query (`src/adapters/fs.rs:3056-3073`), so a misfiled row inside `milestones/A/task-runs.ndjson` will change A's active bead/progress or appear in A's audit results instead of surfacing corruption.","rationale":"The new explicit `milestone_id` field is supposed to make lineage self-contained; without read-time validation, the system can still answer the wrong milestone for \"what happened to bead X?\"."},{"body":"The implementation still ships a large legacy-repair layer for runless rows and paired start/completion rows even though the task explicitly said no backward-compatibility, backfill-on-read, or repair paths were needed. The relevant logic is in `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:300-553` and is exercised by write paths in `src/adapters/fs.rs:2568-3050`. Those paths silently merge, backfill, and delete task-run rows instead of failing fast, which weakens the audit trail for the new schema and makes controller/data bugs much harder to diagnose.","rationale":"This is a significant maintainability and correctness risk, not a cosmetic concern: the store now rewrites lineage history in ways the accepted schema no longer requires."}],"summary":"Tests pass, but I found three issues in the shipped implementation: missing-milestone mutations can poison the workspace, the new `milestone_id` field is not enforced on read/query paths, and the code still contains a broad legacy-repair layer that the task explicitly ruled out."}